         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ As it seems not to be known that any species of Tribulus have poisonous effects, it may be worthy of notice that Mr. Henry Cooke informs me of poison cases on his sheep-run at the Ashburton River, ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">85.07.00e</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To the Gardeners' Chronicle</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found. The text given here is from '</seg>
                     <seg style="">
                        <name key="Tribulus%20platypteris">Tribulus platypteris</name> as a poison', in</seg>
                     <seg style=""> 'Home correspondence', </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Gardeners' chronicle</seg>
                     <seg style="">, 29 August 1885, p. 274 (B</seg>85.08.01). Probable typesetting error: <seg style="">platypteris = platypterus?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <seg style="">As it seems not to be known that any species of Tribulus have poisonous effects, it may be worthy of notice that Mr. Henry Cooke informs me of poison cases on his sheep-run at the Ashburton River,</seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Pilbarra region, WA.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> ascribed to this plant. This gentleman writes as follows :— "I have sheep constantly dying in the neighbourhood where it is growing. It will kill pigeons, as the natives in their wild state steep the bark in water and lay it close to springs; the birds then come and drink out of the yandus</seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Typesetters' error for</seg>
                        <seg style=""> yandies? '</seg>
                        <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Yandy, tjardoo</seg>
                        <seg style="">: Long shallow oval dish, of wood sometimes, but now almost always of sheet-iron': glossary of Pilbari words in a documentary novel by D. Stuart (1959), p. 158.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> that hold the water, and die. It also stupefies or kills fish, so that the natives can get them."</seg>
               <note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Complete letter not found.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
               <seg style="">As other <name key="Zygophyleae">Zygophyleae</name>,</seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Zygophylleae?</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> at least some <name key="Zygophyllum">Zygophyllum</name>s, have proved poisonous to pastoral animals both in South Africa and various places in Australia, we can hardly doubt that species of Tribulus are deleterious also. To overcome this difficulty in North-Western Australia, I have sent seeds of the Teosinte, which giant grass I first introduced into the Australian colonies and Polynesia, and which on the Ashburton River would thrive to perfection, so as to soon overpower the Tribulus.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Ferd. von Mueller</seg>
               <seg style="">. </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">Tribulus </seg>
               <seg style="">platypteris</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">
                  <name key="Zygophyleae">Zygophyleae</name>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">
                  <name key="Zygophyllum">Zygophyllum</name>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
